# 2️⃣ Sliding Window Technique

---

## First Understand the Problem

Suppose the array is:

```text
2 1 5 1 3 2
```

Find the **maximum sum of any 3 consecutive elements**.

---

### Brute Force

Check:

```text
2+1+5
1+5+1
5+1+3
1+3+2
```

Works, but repeats calculations.

---

## Better Idea

Think of a window.

Size = 3

First window:

```text
[2 1 5] 1 3 2
```

Sum = 8

Now slide it one step.

```text
2 [1 5 1] 3 2
```

Instead of recalculating:

Subtract:

```text
2
```

Add:

```text
1
```

New Sum:

```text
8 - 2 + 1 = 7
```

Slide again:

```text
2 1 [5 1 3] 2
```

New Sum:

```text
7 - 1 + 3 = 9
```

Continue until the end.

---

# Why Does It Work?

Neighboring windows share most elements.

Instead of recomputing everything,

just:

```text
Remove old element
+
Add new element
```

---

# Mental Model

Imagine looking through a train window.

You don't jump to a new train every second.

The same window **slides**, showing new scenery.

---

# Time Complexity

Brute Force:

```text
O(n × k)
```

Sliding Window:

```text
O(n)
```

---

# Common Uses

* Maximum subarray sum of size K
* Longest substring
* Minimum window substring
* Anagram problems
* Average of subarrays

---

# Two Pointers vs Sliding Window

| Two Pointers           | Sliding Window                  |
| ---------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| Usually two ends       | Usually one moving window       |
| Often on sorted arrays | Usually on consecutive elements |
| Finds pairs/positions  | Finds best subarray/substring   |

---

# Interview Clues

If the question says:

> **"Two numbers"**

Think:

```text
Two Pointers
```

If the question says:

> **"Contiguous / Consecutive subarray or substring"**

Think:

```text
Sliding Window
```

